 define the responsibilities of employers and contractors involved in work that affects or takes place near processes covered by the regulations to ensure the safety of both plant and contractor employees and the potential effects on public and environmental receptors (RMP only).  This document describes the procedures, training, engineering controls and emergency response procedures implemented by SDSD to prevent or minimize the release of hazardous chemicals from its covered processes. 

It is the policy of SDSD that the receipt, storage and handling of chlorine and sulfur dioxide be done in a manner that meets regulatory requirements and minimizes the probability and severity of accidental releases of chlorine and/or sulfur dioxide into the atmosphere, in order to protect the health and safety of its workers, the public and the environment.  In order to accomplish this goal, SDSD has performed the following tasks:

?    Gathered safety information on the process, equipment and procedures involving chlorine and sulfur dioxide; 
?    Performed a structured process hazard analysis (PHA) and evaluated external events that might affect the process; 
?    Performed an off-site consequences analysis of defined release scenarios; 
?    Established a written program for prevention and mitigation of accidental releases; and 
?    Established a written emergency action plan coordinated with emergency response agencies.

